How it works
When a user first hits the VIP, HAProxy picks a backend server and adds a cookie value to the response:
User hits 192.168.0.182:8089
         ↓
HAProxy picks cs-mgmt1 and sets cookie:
JSESSIONID=abc123~cs1
         ↓
Next request comes in with that cookie
         ↓
HAProxy reads ~cs1 and sends to cs-mgmt1 every time
So cs1 and cs2 are just sticky session identifiers — HAProxy appends them to the existing JSESSIONID cookie to track which server the user belongs to.

You can name them anything meaningful
haproxyserver cs-mgmt1 192.168.0.180:8080 check cookie node1
server cs-mgmt2 192.168.0.181:8080 check cookie node2
or
haproxyserver cs-mgmt1 192.168.0.180:8080 check cookie apcs1
server cs-mgmt2 192.168.0.181:8080 check cookie apcs2
The name itself doesn't matter — just needs to be unique per server so HAProxy can distinguish which backend to route to. cs1 and cs2 are perfectly fine to keep as is.
